Part 1

1)

  1. For backward elimination, beds will be deleted first because it has the highest p value

  2. For forward selection, size will be the first variable added because it has the highest significance (with p value = 0)

  3. I believe this is because the correlation between beds and price is not telling the whole story, when a house has more beds, it is probably because it has a much larger size. Therefore when controlling for everything and looking for the isolated regression between price and beds, the p value is higher.

data('house.selling.price.2')

PRESS

PRESS <- function(linear.model) {
  pr <- residuals(linear.model)/(1 - lm.influence(linear.model)$hat)
  sum(pr^2)}

model <- lm(Volume ~ Height + Girth, data = trees)

par(mfrow = c(2,3)); plot(model, which = 1:6)

Because of these plots the following assumptions are violated: Linearity, Constant variance, and influential observation.

This can be seen by:

1.)Linearity - curvature in residuals vs.fitted graph 2.)Constant variance is violated - Increasing/Decreasing in Scale Location model 3.)Influential observation - Cooks distance is larger than 4/n (=2)

data('florida')

model_2<-lm(Buchanan ~ Bush, data = florida)

par(mfrow = c(2,3)); plot(model_2, which = 1:6)

Yes, Palm Beachs location in terms of Scale-Location, Residuals vs.fitted and Leverage can be deemed an outlier

Part 2

  1. My research question I will be exploring in my final project is does age affect if someone trusts the news media?

My hypothesis is that younger age people will trust news media less

  1. Outcome variable: Trust in media Explanatory Variable: Age Other control variables: Education, trust in people in general Dataset source: GSS data explorer
